---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import PageHeader from "../../components/PageHeader.astro";
import CensusEngine from "../../novascope/components/CensusEngine.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="The cluster census — Anna Rosen"
  description="Sample a star cluster from the initial mass function and read it on the H–R diagram — colours, temperatures and luminosities computed live from validated ZAMS physics."
  path="/explore/census"
>
  <PageHeader eyebrow="Explore · interactive" title="The cluster census">
    <Fragment slot="lede">
      A cluster is a <em>draw</em> from the initial mass function, not a smooth curve
      painted across the sky. Sample one here, then read it two ways at once — as points
      in space and as points on the Hertzsprung–Russell diagram. Every colour,
      temperature and luminosity is computed on the spot from the same validated ZAMS
      relations my software uses.
    </Fragment>
  </PageHeader>

  <div class="census-page wrap-wide">
    <CensusEngine />

    <div class="census-page__note prose wrap">
      <p>
        Drag the <strong>high-mass slope</strong> and the whole character of the cluster
        shifts: flatten it and a few brilliant blue stars appear in the upper-left of the
        H–R diagram; steepen it and they vanish into a crowd of faint red dwarfs. Cool red
        stars are always the many; the rare hot stars are always the few — and yet the few
        are the whole story, because luminosity climbs so steeply with mass that a handful
        of O stars outshine, and out-push, everything else combined.
      </p>
      <p>
        Change <strong>N</strong> and watch the massive tail <em>flicker</em>. That is not
        a rendering glitch — it is sampling noise. A small cluster genuinely might not draw
        a single massive star, which is exactly why the high-mass end of the mass function
        is so hard to measure and so easy to get wrong. Nothing here is choreographed: the
        stars are re-sampled from the mass function in your browser, and the diagram is
        derived, not drawn.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .census-page { padding-block: var(--space-l) var(--space-3xl); }
  .census-page__note { margin-block-start: var(--space-2xl); }
</style>
